args: This is for you, Catherine!\nDad said to give it to you and tell you to\nplease do your shopping at his shop!
Well, since you're pretty bucks up and the\nmayor's daughter and all, we wantedâ€”
To throw me a birthday party?
To think Becky and Sandy now haunt my\nvery dreams... Oh, will the dreaded day\nof my birth never arrive?!
(Once this birthday is over with, I can\nfinally let go of my foolish expectation.)
(...The expectation that someone will\ngenuinely celebrate with me.)
Well, THIS is an impressive feast\nfor the first meal of the day.
I am afraid I got a touch carried away.
Wait, YOU did all this?! Yerself?
In fact, Catherine has quite\nthe deft hand in the kitchen.
Well, kick my butt and call me rumpy.\nI figured you'd have spent yer life gettin'\nfed by chefs at yer mansion.
We do, of course, have a fantastic chef\nwho resides on our estate.
And by watching this chef at work,\nI learned to cook for myself.
Elisanne, might you train me in the spear\nwhen you have a spare moment?
I can ill afford to repeat the same mistake\nI committed yesterday, after all.
Your desire for improvement is impressive.
Naturally! Even my aspirations are perfect!
Is this ï¼‚bein' perfectï¼‚ deal really that\nimportant to ya? 'Cause ya sure do\ntalk about it all the damn time.
Of course it is important to me, sir!\nWhy would you even ask such a question?
I was just wonderin' if maybe all this\nperfection stuff wasn't tirin' ya out.
I mean, yer young and dumb,\nand bein' young and dumb means\nyer allowed to make a few mistakes.
I am sorry to say I do not possess\nsuch a soft line of thought.
Because being perfect is all I have...
Have you been staying in this castle\never since you left town?
What are you two doing here?!\nCan't you see I wish to be left alone?!
I'm sorry, Cat. This is all my fault.\nI know I hurt your feelings.
Look, I can't claim to understand\nevery part of what you're thinking...
But I know Becky and I think of you\nas our very dear friend.
...Your friends have gone back\nto Quinbell, Catherine.
You know, you're not the same Catherine\nI remember from the village.
You used to hold friends close, but now\nyou talk about ï¼‚choosing them wisely.ï¼‚
All I'm saying is that if you want to talk\nabout anything, I have a spare ear.
Have you ever found your station\nas a prince to be...painful?
Surely people are constantly assessing\nyou based solely on your title, yes?
Oh sure, that happens all the timeâ€”\nbut I wouldn't call it ï¼‚painful.ï¼‚
That title enables me to do a lot of things\nI'd never be able to do otherwise.
Plus, for every social climber who sees\nme as just another rung on the ladder,\nI have a friend who sees me for who I am.
In addition to carrying yourself with the\ntrue caliber of a prince, you have filled\nyour life with allies good and true.
You also have friends, Catherine.\nHeck, I've met them.
I thought so once, but have since learned\neven they only see me for my situation.
I am a mayor's daughter. A rich girl.\nA tool to be used and discarded.\nAnd I am SICK of it!
This is why I strive for perfection:\nTo prove I am capable of anything,\nregardless of my station at birth.
All I want is for people to look at me\nand see a person of worth. Not a title\nor a fortunate better, but a PERSON.
But once I came here, I realized I am as\nfar from perfection as when I started.
In the end, I'm nothing but a rich child\nwith a powerful father. And even those\ntwo see me that way...
Please, save your breath. People clearly\nsee you for the man you are, which means\nyou could never understand my plight.
You're more than your birth, Catherine.\nDo you know how I know that?
Because NO ONE is just that.\nWe're all individuals with our own\nvoices and our own unique value.
Just try to remember that, all right?
I suppose your life allows you to believe\nthose words...
